		<item>
		<title>
		By: Darius Belejevas		</title>
		<link>https://jamesclear.vercel.app/habits-visibility-method#comment-277</link>

		<dc:creator><![CDATA[Darius Belejevas]]></dc:creator>
		<pubDate>Fri, 25 Jan 2013 11:34:07 +0000</pubDate>
		<guid isPermaLink="false">https://jamesclear-com.uar9g7bv-liquidwebsites.com/?p=3668#comment-277</guid>

					<description><![CDATA[In reply to &lt;a href=&quot;https://jamesclear.vercel.app/habits-visibility-method#comment-275&quot;&gt;Tammy R&lt;/a&gt;.

Hey Tammy,

There&#039;s an interesting idea by Eben Pagan, that it takes much more effort to actively stop doing the bad things than to do the good things. The solution in this case is to focus our willpower on doing the right things and let the bad things take care of themselves.

Admittedly, this does not work in every situation, but I had really great results with this approach for increasing productivity. For example, I would focus on several key items I need to do on that day and wouldn&#039;t get angry on myself if after doing them I would engage in something &quot;bad&quot;.

Interestingly, over the course of several months I noticed a significant rise in the time spent doing &quot;good&quot; things and in turn the amount of time spent doing &quot;bad&quot; things decreased without making conscious effort.

For eating this would mean to focus on fulfilling hunger with good foods/drinks. It&#039;s really much easier to resist junk food when we&#039;re feeling satisfied. :)

Maybe this approach can be applied in your situation too.]]></description>
			<content:encoded><![CDATA[<p>In reply to <a href="https://jamesclear.vercel.app/habits-visibility-method#comment-275">Tammy R</a>.</p>
<p>Hey Tammy,</p>
<p>There&#8217;s an interesting idea by Eben Pagan, that it takes much more effort to actively stop doing the bad things than to do the good things. The solution in this case is to focus our willpower on doing the right things and let the bad things take care of themselves.</p>
<p>Admittedly, this does not work in every situation, but I had really great results with this approach for increasing productivity. For example, I would focus on several key items I need to do on that day and wouldn&#8217;t get angry on myself if after doing them I would engage in something &#8220;bad&#8221;.</p>
<p>Interestingly, over the course of several months I noticed a significant rise in the time spent doing &#8220;good&#8221; things and in turn the amount of time spent doing &#8220;bad&#8221; things decreased without making conscious effort.</p>
<p>For eating this would mean to focus on fulfilling hunger with good foods/drinks. It&#8217;s really much easier to resist junk food when we&#8217;re feeling satisfied. :)</p>
<p>Maybe this approach can be applied in your situation too.</p>
]]></content:encoded>
		
